## Summary

I've successfully identified and fixed the bug in the jsoup parser. Here's what was done:

### Problem Analysis
The test `org.jsoup.parser.ParserTest::handlesDataOnlyTags` was failing because `<script>` tags in the body were not being handled as data-only tags. The issue was in `TreeBuilderState.java` in the `InBody` state processing.

### Root Cause
In the `InBody` state, certain elements like `<style>`, `<meta>`, `<link>`, etc. are processed as if they were in the head (using `tb.process(t, InHead)`), which properly handles them as data-only tags. However, `<script>` was missing from this list, so it was falling through to the default processing which doesn't treat it as a data-only tag.

### The Fix
Added `"script"` to the list of element names in the `InBody` state that get processed as if they were in the head state:

```java
// Before
} else if (StringUtil.in(name, "base", "basefont", "bgsound", "command", "link", "meta", "noframes", "style", "title")) {
    return tb.process(t, InHead);
}

// After  
} else if (StringUtil.in(name, "base", "basefont", "bgsound", "command", "link", "meta", "noframes", "script", "style", "title")) {
    return tb.process(t, InHead);
}
```

### Verification
- The triggering test `org.jsoup.parser.ParserTest::handlesDataOnlyTags` now passes
- All other tests continue to pass (no regression)
- The fix ensures that `<script>` elements in the body are treated the same way as in the head, with their content stored as `DataNode` objects rather than `TextNode` objects, making them accessible via `.data()` but not `.text()`.

The patch is saved in `blind_fix.patch` and correctly addresses the bug without breaking existing functionality.

